# This file is entirely OPTIONAL. LightNVR runs with zero configuration:
# `docker compose up -d --build` works with no .env file at all. Everything
# below is an advanced override for power users/scripted deployments - normal
# setup (accounts, email alerts, storage, retention) all happens through the
# web UI after first boot, with no file editing required.
#
# To use any of these, copy this file to .env, uncomment what you need, and
# restart the backend container.

# Ports exposed on the host. Changing a published Docker port can only be
# done by recreating the container, so this is the one setting that
# genuinely can't move into the GUI - every Dockerized app has this same
# constraint, it isn't specific to LightNVR.
# WEB_PORT=8080
# BACKEND_PORT=8000

# Pins the JWT signing secret instead of letting it auto-generate on first
# boot. Only useful for running multiple backend instances that need to
# accept each other's tokens - a single instance doesn't need this.
# JWT_SECRET_KEY=

# Unattended admin bootstrap for scripted/headless deployments. Leave unset
# and the GUI setup wizard creates the first admin account on first visit
# instead - that's the normal path for everyone else.
# ADMIN_USERNAME=
# ADMIN_PASSWORD=

# Frontend build-time API base path. Only relevant for custom reverse-proxy
# setups that don't match the bundled nginx config; the default already
# works for the standard docker-compose.yml setup.
# VITE_API_BASE_URL=/api

# Database connection string. Infra-level setting, not exposed in the GUI on
# purpose - the running app can't safely repoint its own DB connection from
# inside itself. Must keep the +aiosqlite driver if you change this.
# DATABASE_URL=sqlite+aiosqlite:////data/lightnvr.db

# Where recordings are written on the host. Default is an in-repo folder;
# point it at a dedicated disk's mount path to keep footage off the OS disk.
# scripts/install-linux.sh --storage-path=... sets this for you (and checks
# the path is a real mount); this is the same thing done by hand. Setting it
# here instead of editing docker-compose.yml is what keeps `git pull` clean.
# PRIMARY_STORAGE_PATH=/mnt/nvr-storage
# BACKUP_STORAGE_PATH=/mnt/nvr-backup

# Selects which compose files docker loads. Set by install-linux.sh when you
# enable camera scanning, so plain `docker compose up` pulls in the macvlan
# override automatically (no two-file -f command). The separator is ':' on
# Linux, ';' on Windows.
# COMPOSE_FILE=docker-compose.yml:docker-compose.macvlan.yml

# Only needed if you use docker-compose.macvlan.yml (an optional override,
# not applied by default) to make the "Scan network" ONVIF button work on
# Linux - see docs/linux-production-install.md for the full walkthrough.
# All four are specific to your machine; there's no sensible default, and
# the override refuses to start if any are missing rather than guessing.
#
# LAN_SCAN_INTERFACE: the host's physical network interface name. Find it
# with `ip route | grep default` (the "dev <name>" at the end). Must be a
# wired NIC - macvlan doesn't work reliably over Wi-Fi. On a VM, the VM's
# own virtual NIC (e.g. Proxmox's ens18) is fine; Wi-Fi only matters for the
# physical host underneath it.
# LAN_SCAN_INTERFACE=

# LAN_SCAN_SUBNET / LAN_SCAN_GATEWAY: your LAN's subnet (CIDR) and default
# gateway. Find both with `ip route | grep default` (gives the gateway) and
# `ip -4 addr show` (gives your own address + subnet mask, e.g. a /24 or,
# less commonly, a wider /22 like some routers use).
# LAN_SCAN_SUBNET=
# LAN_SCAN_GATEWAY=

# LAN_SCAN_BACKEND_IP: a free, unused IP within LAN_SCAN_SUBNET to assign
# the backend container - it becomes a real, separate device on your LAN.
# Pick something outside your router's DHCP range if you know it, and
# confirm it's actually free first (`ping -c1 <candidate-ip>` - no reply
# means it's very likely unused).
# LAN_SCAN_BACKEND_IP=
